<subSubSection pageId="181" pageNumber="182" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="181" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Rawi &amp; Alizzi</emphasis>
34452 is atypical because of short side branchlets, these and the main branches terminating in slender sharp spines. It is suggested that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sa'ad" authorityYear="1967" baseAuthorityName="Rech. fil." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus cateniflorus" order="Solanales" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cateniflorus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Convolvulus cateniflorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss., Diagn. Pl. Orient. 7: 26. 1846. (Boissier" authorityYear="1846" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus oxyphyllus" order="Solanales" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oxyphyllus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Convolvulus oxyphyllus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the shorter, less spinescent, more densely tomentose stems and solitary flowers (Rechinger 1964: 483) but all kinds of intermediates can be found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
